segments.text: That's the great big overall single thing.
This air movement is the one specific thing.
Okay, let's talk about the air movement that you were telling me about yesterday.
But first I have a question.
Now, you had about 1,600 men in your battalion.
Well, we had more than that when we got into this place.
Okay, when you commanded, how many men were under your command?
Well, at one time, there were about 4,500.
About 4,500?
And you took those men and you divided them into groups, and then you sent them out.
That's right.
And how large was each group?
It depended on the mission.
And it sort of depended on the organization.
A battalion...

usually works best as a battalion yeah now there there were separate company types in the unit there were some detachments there were some groups and it depended on on what the mission was and where they went we might send the group headquarters to go along with two of its battalions to a particular place and then another part of his
as a group staff would take the other battalion on a subsequent mission or a mission at the same time somewhere else.
We not only divided our staff into this diversified operation, we took our subordinate units, which were groups and battalions, and had them do the same thing to the degree that they were capable of.
Now, the lower the type headquarters you get, the less you can split it up.
In other words, you couldn't split a company headquarters and let its company go hither and yonder, battalion less so.
A group can do more so, and a brigade could do it to a great degree.
So it depended on who and where and what the mission was.
There was no pattern.
It sounds to me that this would really increase the officers'
desire and motivation.
Absolutely.
Because they'd have response.
Your junior officers or your middle grade officers would have much more responsibility on their own than if they were just under the general's command.
Absolutely.
We utilized many of our staff officers just as I think the T.O.
and E. envisioned them.
For instance, we'd go ahead of everybody else to summer camp.
We'd go to the brigade headquarters.
And we started going to Fort Bullis, which is out of San Antonio.
We went there, and we didn't busy ourselves at all with this year's mission.
We went there and looked at next year's mission.
We were the big planner.
We planned the big picture for next year.
And the reason we went there, right next door to 4th Army,
who was our operating headquarter.
In other words, we were under Fourth Army.
And they were in control of all these areas, see.
They could say, you can go here, you can go yonder, these people.
In other words, they were our headquarter.
So we satellited right outside of San Antonio where we could plan next year's big picture.
And then when

one of the groups, for instance, would go to Fort Bullis or, I mean, Fort Sill or Fort Chaffee, then I'd attach one of my staff officers to summer camp with that group to speak for the headquarters, to be the reconnaissance officer for the headquarters or to interpret plans or really just to be there
They're contacted with the brigade headquarters.
But here's the group commander out there.
He's operating.
He's the sole commander there.
He's running the show.
And we've all gone back home.
Now, each one of these satellite operations, and I'd go and visit them or my deputy a day or a half a day or whatever just to see what was going on.
But we always had one of our...

headquarters officers there as a liaison officer he didn't have any command function at all he was not he didn't interfere with the command at all but we fanned out and that gave them a responsibility and gave them a feeling well I'm being used like I ought to be used so it was a great morale builder and it was and they've continued this program that's right it's uh
I think once or twice since then they've pulled the brigade back pretty much together for some specific reason, but I think the concept is still very much like we started it.
Do you know if any other reserve units in the country started this kind after you began this?
Did anybody else pick up?
Well, I was told by Fourth Army people that they were going to instill it in
They subsequently made it Fifth Army, and they had the unit up in Chicago under them then.
And I'm told that they liked the idea well.
Now, whether they ever instituted it or not to the degree that we did, I'm not sure.
But they were certainly totally 100% sold on the concept.
We saved many hundreds of thousands of dollars

because we had the man hours to spend on something, and the class one installation engineers had some monies to buy things with, but we made his money go a long way when we furnished the personnel to do it with.
Sure, sure.
So it, that was one of the greatest accomplishments that I was able to
help direct.
And when we sat down with them and talked about it, they almost threw us out of the office.
Never worked.
Now, tell me about your other experience.
Well, the one single thing that gave me a great deal of satisfaction was to institute a program of airlifting a construction company to summer camp, along with their equipment.
They've carried troops to summer camp by air for years.
That's no feat.
But I could envision needing a construction company in Puerto Rico or Virgin Islands or somewhere that we have a responsibility and need to get them there.
They've never gotten on an airplane with equipment or never loaded equipment or whatever.
So I propose to
Fourth Army that we do such a thing for something.
What year was that?
Do you remember?
I don't know.
We did it both the last two years.
Let's see, 70 and 71.
That's probably right, 70 and 71.
I think that's right.
So you reposed it about 1969.
That's correct.
In fact, it may have been 68.
I worked on it for a couple of years.
But I proposed we do it, and they, again, sort of laughed at it.
And it was a different group than I sold the program before to.
They'd all gone.
But they went forward with the request and came back with a routine refusal.
So then I asked them to try it again, and it got a few headquarters further, but it was turned down because it said it
The equipment was not available, and the funds were not available.
In one of our diversified work programs, we had built an 18-hole golf course for Kelly Air Force Base.
And one of the reserve Air Force commanders there was one of the ones involved in our lesson with Kelly Air Force Base.
And we built a great facility there.
The basics.
We didn't do the refinements like the grass and some of the things that only the golf pros can do.
But we built the bridges and the roads and the rough work on the golf course and laid the irrigation system, built the pro shop.
We did this over a four-year period.
So we had done a great deal of work for them, just a whole lot of work.
And they would give me nearly anything I asked for.
I got a jet airplane to go to Virginia one time just because they thought I needed it.
But anyhow, I had gotten well acquainted with this wing commander down there at reserve.
And he had subsequently been assigned as the chief Air Force reserve in Washington.
So I had the thought, well, I might be able to appeal to him to help me on this program.
So I saw the Chief of Army Reserve, who I knew very well, who was a Texan, General Sutton.
Told him what I was going to do.
Asked him if he had any objection, and he said he had none.
Said, just give me a copy of your letters that you write to the Air Force, because it's cross-service.
So I wrote to my friend in Washington, the Chief Air Force Reserve, and told him... What was his name?
Still haven't thought of it.
I'll get it.
I'll get it in a minute.
And he's an Aggie.
Oh, that's right.
So I wrote him a letter, and very shortly, like 10 days, I got a response back through...
He's dead.
Oh, that's right.
I got a response back through Robbins Air Force Base in Georgia, which is reserve headquarters for some Air Force area, probably this whole part of the United States, can't you?
They didn't say that he had written to him or anything.
They just wrote me a letter as 420th Commander and said they understood I had a flying mission that I would like to accomplish for summer camp.
And the two questions were, where do you want to go and what do you want to haul?
So from there, it was accomplished.
We hauled a million pounds of men and equipment to Albuquerque, to Sandia Base.

landed at Kirtland Air Force Base, and we departed from two places, from Corpus Christi Naval Air Station and from Bergstrom in Austin, divided the company, part of them were there and part of them here, and part of the equipment, and flew them to summer camp.
We let them work for two weeks, and incidentally, the day they got there, they unloaded their equipment and they were working 1,000 miles away.
My goodness.
So it proved the point that I was after is that we could get in an airplane and go somewhere real quick, be working the same day.
How many men were in on this?
It was just a company size, 200 or less, just regular engineer construction company.
But we'd put, I remember one particular load was a motor grader and 10 men.
They just got in the airplane right with the motor grader.
When the airplane landed, they cranked up the motor grader and drove it out of there, and they were out working in 20 minutes.
So we had, oh, I've forgotten how many C-124s, but like 10 or 12 that went from both Naval Air Station
Now, they made one or two trips each.
They didn't fly it all at one pop.
But anyhow, it worked great.
We sent the company there.
At the end of two weeks, we flew personnel home.
We flew another company of people out there, and they took the equipment that was there and worked it for two weeks.
Then they unloaded it and brought it home.
So we really got training for two companies in a four-week period.
We got very good remarks out of that operation.
So the next year, Army provided for us to get in on this deal.
They provided the opportunity for us to go to Florida to the conference where they allocate airplanes for this type of thing.
We had our man down there that told them what we needed to haul and where and all this.
They got in on that the next year and got us down there.
So we did it two years in a row.
The second year... And where did you go the second year?
Same place.
Okay.
Because of the fact that we had this big, nice air base there that we could land.
And then Sandia Base is right adjacent to it where we can work.
So it is an ideal situation.
The next year, then, they gave us the C-141, the Starlifter jet plane.
And we went from the Naval Air Station in Dallas and Bergstrom in Austin that year.
So we really coordinated with three different takeoff points, Army, Navy, and Air Force.
And it sounds like more recently now the American government is considering mobile Army units and
And they're talking especially with the problems in Iran and the problems in Afghanistan, how we need this type of mobility in our service.
And it sounds like your idea was sort of a predecessor to that.
I read that.
Now, you know, World War II had some mobile engineer equipment that they could fly, but it was miniature stuff.
Mm-hmm.
It was little stuff built for that purpose.
But my idea was taking conventional equipment, bulldozers, motor graders, trailers, rollers, water tanks, this type of thing, and go with it.
Of course, we'd have to take a blade off a dozer because it had a lot of weight and width and all this.
But it was a great mission in loading it and tying it down
Our people got right in on that.
And they were, I think they enjoyed it too.
Is this type of mission still being performed?
I don't believe it is.
And I'm sure due to curtailment of funds and various things.
And I really don't believe that they did it the year after I retired.
I think they did it, we only did it the two years, I believe.
I'm not absolutely certain, but I'm certain they're not doing it anymore.
Of course, they're not doing a lot of things that funds make available.
Oh, sure.
Absolutely.
Now that we've talked about some of your accomplishments when you were commanding, let's talk about shortcomings.
Were there some shortcomings?
Were there some things that you wanted to accomplish but just couldn't?
Oh, there's got to always be...
person that hangs his wagon to a star is not ever going to accomplish all the things he wants to.
I'm not real sure that I can enumerate specifically things that I would have liked to accomplish.
I'm sure that our level of training could have been better.
We could have
because I had more people trained in certain ways.
But to specifically enumerate, I'm not sure.
I was fortunate in commanding during the years that we had waiting lists for people wanting to get in.
There was one or two years that we had a little problem with strengths,
uh, nothing like they've suffered since then.
So, you know, strengths weren't really a problem.
Turnover was always a problem.
I mean, uh, you'd always got new people that somebody was getting out, and, but, uh, and I had some fine officers, had some fine non-commissioned officers.
Uh, I was in that unit, uh, twenty years, I believe, twenty,
Yeah, 20 years, 51 to 71.
And it was a rewarding time as far as accomplishments and frustrations were few.
We had them, but I can't really look back and say there were a lot of things that we ought to have done that we didn't.
I know nobody's as efficient as they'd like to be, but it really went off well.
My superiors were kind to me and just these things that I've talked about and working with us.
Once they found out that we weren't just blowing our horn, we could accomplish something, they gave us the wooden water and we spent it.
Okay.
Well, let's end our conversation for this afternoon and have one more chat Friday or so.
Okay.
All right.
This is a test.
This is Terry Anderson.
Today is August 1st, 1980.
This is the third and last interview with General Hanover.
This is a test.
